I disagree that refusing to help SCP-3133 would be considered  given that multiple people must actively administer the shock, maintain the collar, feed the dog, and ensure proper containment. Even if the collar was set to automatically administer the shock, someone must check and maintain the collar, which would be the moral equivalent of pulling the lever. I also disagree that people who are aware of the SCP's true nature would be morally justified in directly harming it. Changing the morals of the Foundation does not directly harm anyone, it's the consequences that harm people, which, on a moral level, are out of the control of the individuals involved in 3133's containment. Sorry if that argument made no sense, but I wanted to express my viewpoint.

I love this SCP and the idea of an SCP changing the moral views of the people around it is a tough thing to describe. Morality is such an abstract concept, so the more specific you can make the SCP the easier it will be for people to understand.

+1 from me, keep it up







